variousremarks: This is the account given by the captain to a sub-investor. The ship first went to Africa, was captured by the British and sent to Plymouth. It was then freed and went back to Africa, then Martinique and Nantes. Quickly after, he departed again in a direct voyage to get more sugar and arrived back to Nantes in 1817

variousremarks: Only the first voyage is a slave one (three ships, though, so 3 voyages) Contradictory informations about the captain’s names. We have both a compte de désarmement and the « répartitions ». To prevent double counting, I classify the compte de désarmement as « Transactions during the voyage ».
